{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U1BoP6PfF2uMV7oTDf3wTD","type":"tool_result","content":"25-## Executive Summary\n26-\n27:codeharness currently executes stories sequentially — one at a time, one framework at a time. A 19-story sprint takes 8+ hours of wall-clock time. This PRD adds **parallel execution** at two levels: parallel epics via git worktrees and parallel stories within epics, cutting sprint time proportionally to the parallelism factor.\n28-\n29-The workflow engine gains a **hierarchical flow model** with three levels. Sprint-level flow schedules epics (potentially in parallel). Epic-level flow schedules stories and runs an epic retro on completion. Story-level flow is the existing `implement → verify → loop` pipeline. Each level has distinct lifecycle hooks: per-story telemetry (zero-token, engine-handled) and per-epic retrospectives (LLM-powered, one call per epic instead of per-session).\n30-\n31:Parallel execution requires **isolation**. Each parallel dispatch gets its own git worktree — a separate working directory on a separate branch. Stories within a worktree execute sequentially. When an epic completes, its worktree branch merges back to main. If merge conflicts occur, a merge agent resolves them with context from both branches.\n32-\n33-Three additional optimizations ship with this: **`agent: null` tasks** let the engine handle telemetry without LLM dispatch (saving ~$120-180/sprint on retro overhead), **verify flag propagation** moves flag-setting from the evaluator to the engine (fixing unreliable verification), and **coverage deduplication** eliminates redundant coverage runs during verification.\n--\n35-### What Makes This Special\n36-\n37:- **Worktree-isolated parallelism** — each parallel epic runs in its own git worktree. No shared mutable state during execution. Conflicts surface only at merge time, handled by a merge agent.\n38-- **Hierarchical flow model** — sprint → epic → story, each with its own lifecycle. Not a flat task queue — a structured execution DAG with dependency-aware scheduling.\n39-- **Zero-token engine tasks** — `agent: null` tasks execute without LLM dispatch. Telemetry collection, flag setting, and state bookkeeping become free operations.\n40-- **Multi-lane TUI** — parallel execution visualized as concurrent workflow lanes, each showing its own story progress, driver, and cost.\n41:- **Proportional speedup** — 2 parallel worktrees = ~2x faster sprints. Configurable up from there.\n42-\n43-## Project Classification\n--\n45-- **Project Type:** Developer tool — npm CLI extending existing workflow engine\n46-- **Domain:** General software development tooling\n47:- **Complexity:** High — git worktree lifecycle, multi-process orchestration, merge conflict resolution, hierarchical state machines, multi-lane TUI rendering\n48-- **Project Context:** Brownfield — workflow engine, driver layer, TUI, state management all exist. This adds parallelism, hierarchy, and merge on top.\n49-\n--\n59-### Business Success\n60-\n61:- **3-month goal:** Parallel epic execution with worktrees, merge agent, and cross-worktree test validation working end-to-end. 2x speedup demonstrated.\n62-- **6-month goal:** Parallel stories within epics. DAG-based scheduling. Configurable parallelism at 3-4 lanes.\n63-- **Cost reduction:** ~$120-180/sprint from retro optimization. Additional savings from reduced wall-clock time.\n--\n65-### Technical Success\n66-\n67:- **Worktree lifecycle:** Create, execute, merge, cleanup — fully automated. No orphaned worktrees.\n68:- **State consistency:** Hierarchical state consistent across parallel worktrees. No corruption from concurrent writes.\n69-- **Merge reliability:** Merge agent resolves conflicts on first attempt for >95% of merges.\n70:- **Cross-worktree validation:** Full test suite passes on merged result before accepting.\n71-- **TUI responsiveness:** Multi-lane rendering at 15 FPS with 2-4 concurrent lanes.\n72-- **Backward compatibility:** `max_parallel: 1` produces identical behavior to current sequential execution.\n--\n81-| Epic retro cost | <$10/epic (vs $50+ per-session) | Cost tracking |\n82-| TUI FPS with 2 lanes | 15 FPS | Measured render |\n83:| Orphaned worktrees | 0 after sprint | `git worktree list` |\n84-| Post-merge test pass rate | 100% | Test suite on merge |\n85-\n--\n91-- `agent: null` tasks — engine-handled, zero-token telemetry\n92-- `scope: per-epic` — epic-level lifecycle hooks (retro)\n93:- Parallel epic execution with git worktree isolation (configurable, default 2)\n94:- Worktree lifecycle — create branch, create worktree, execute, merge, cleanup\n95-- Merge agent — LLM-powered automatic conflict resolution\n96:- Cross-worktree test validation — full test suite on merged result before accepting\n97-- Engine verify flag propagation — engine sets flags from output contract\n98-- Coverage deduplication — dev phase only, verify reads from contract\n--\n102-### Post-MVP (Growth)\n103-\n104:- Parallel stories within epics — nested worktrees or sequential with faster cycling\n105-- DAG-based epic scheduling — dependency-aware parallel scheduling from epic declarations\n106-- Dynamic parallelism — adjust concurrent lanes based on API rate limits and cost\n--\n117-execution:\n118-  max_parallel: 2\n119:  isolation: worktree\n120-  epic_strategy: parallel\n121-  story_strategy: sequential\n122-```\n123:Runs `codeharness run`. The engine reads the epic dependency graph, identifies epic-10 and epic-14 as independent, and creates two git worktrees: `epic-10-driver-interface` and `epic-14-tui-workflow`.\n124-\n125-**Rising Action:** The TUI shows two lanes:\n--\n136-Done: (none yet)  |  Active: 2 lanes  |  Pending: 4 epics\n137-```\n138:Both epics execute simultaneously, each in its own worktree. Stories within each epic run sequentially.\n139-\n140:**Climax:** Epic 14 finishes first (3 stories vs 5). The engine runs the per-epic telemetry summary, then triggers the epic-14 retro task (analyst agent reads telemetry, produces findings). Then it merges the `epic-14-tui-workflow` branch back to main. The cross-worktree test suite runs on the merged result — all tests pass. The worktree is cleaned up. Lane 2 picks up epic-11 (next independent epic).\n141-\n142-**Resolution:** The sprint completes in 4.5 hours instead of 8+. BMad glances at the TUI — 6 epics done, 2 merge conflicts auto-resolved by the merge agent, 0 manual interventions, total cost $245 (vs $271 sequential due to fewer rate-limit waits).\n--\n160-```\n161-\n162:**Climax:** The merge agent resolves the conflict — both changes are additive, different functions, no semantic overlap. It commits the resolution. The cross-worktree test suite runs — all tests pass.\n163-\n164-**Resolution:** The merge completes automatically. The TUI shows: `[MERGE] epic-11 → main: auto-resolved (1 file)`. BMad never opened a terminal.\n--\n196-| Journey | Capabilities Revealed |\n197-|---------|----------------------|\n198:| **BMad — Parallel Sprint** | Worktree creation, parallel epic scheduling, multi-lane TUI, merge + test validation, worktree cleanup |\n199:| **Engine — Merge Conflict** | Merge agent dispatch, conflict detection, resolution context, cross-worktree test validation |\n200-| **BMad — Telemetry Replaces Retros** | agent: null tasks, scope: per-epic, telemetry NDJSON, epic retro synthesis |\n201-| **Engine — Zero-Token Telemetry** | agent: null execution, output contract data extraction, NDJSON append |\n--\n207-**1. Worktree-Isolated Parallel Execution**\n208-\n209:No existing autonomous coding tool parallelizes across git worktrees. Claude Code's Agent tool supports `isolation: \"worktree\"` for subagents, but no orchestrator manages multiple concurrent worktrees with lifecycle, merge, and test validation.\n210-\n211-**2. Hierarchical Flow Model**\n--\n226-\n227-**Worktree Management:**\n228:- `git worktree add` to create isolated working directories per epic\n229:- Each worktree on its own branch: `epic-{N}-{slug}`\n230:- Stories execute sequentially within worktree\n231:- On epic completion: `git merge` branch into main, run tests, cleanup worktree\n232-\n233-**Hierarchical State:**\n234-- Sprint state: which epics are active, which lanes are occupied\n235:- Epic state: which stories are done/in-progress within this epic's worktree\n236-- Story state: existing task checkpointing (unchanged)\n237:- All state files live in the worktree — no shared mutable state\n238-\n239-**Parallel Orchestration:**\n--\n251-```yaml\n252-execution:\n253:  max_parallel: 2           # concurrent worktrees\n254:  isolation: worktree       # or 'none' for sequential\n255-  merge_strategy: rebase    # or 'merge-commit'\n256-  epic_strategy: parallel   # or 'sequential'\n--\n267-epic_flow:                  # runs when epic completes\n268-  - retro                   # agent: analyst, scope: per-epic\n269:  - merge                   # built-in: merge worktree → main\n270-  - validate                # built-in: run test suite on merged result\n271-```\n--\n283-### Parallel Execution & Worktrees\n284-\n285:- FR6: System can create a git worktree for each parallel epic dispatch\n286:- FR7: System can create a git branch per epic (`epic-{N}-{slug}`)\n287:- FR8: System can execute stories sequentially within a worktree\n288-- FR9: System can manage a lane pool limited by `max_parallel`\n289-- FR10: System can detect epic independence (no dependency on in-progress epics) for parallel scheduling\n290:- FR11: System can clean up worktrees and branches after epic completion and successful merge\n291-\n292-### Merge & Validation\n--\n322-- FR28: System can display a summary bar showing active lanes, total cost, and merge status\n323-- FR29: System can show merge progress and conflict resolution status in the TUI\n324:- FR30: System can render lane completion (worktree merged, tests passed) as a distinct visual state\n325-\n326-### Out of Scope (Explicitly Excluded from MVP)\n--\n338-- NFR3: Telemetry NDJSON write must complete within 10ms per entry\n339-- NFR4: Merge operation (non-conflicting) must complete within 30 seconds\n340:- NFR5: Cross-worktree test suite must complete within the project's normal test timeout\n341-\n342-### Reliability\n343-\n344:- NFR6: If a worktree's execution crashes, other lanes must continue unaffected\n345:- NFR7: If merge fails after 3 agent resolution attempts, escalate to user — do not retry indefinitely\n346:- NFR8: Sprint state must remain consistent across all worktrees — no concurrent write corruption\n347:- NFR9: Orphaned worktrees must be detected and cleaned up on next `codeharness run`\n348-- NFR10: `max_parallel: 1` must produce identical behavior and results to current sequential execution\n349-\n350-### Integration\n351-\n352:- NFR11: Git worktree commands must work with the project's existing git hooks\n353-- NFR12: Worktree branches must not conflict with user's existing branches (prefix with `codeharness/`)\n354-- NFR13: Telemetry NDJSON format must be stable across versions (versioned entries)"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01MhSojYxQi6QD3G7L9MYQcx","session_id":"187035da-d60e-40cf-8aef-09e6134be246","uuid":"ae469a2c-b0ca-48a0-b0b0-66df35b9dabf","timestamp":"2026-04-03T19:21:41.027Z"}
{"type":"system","subtype":"task_progress","task_id":"afc19ee3704ef682d","tool_use_id":"toolu_01MhSojYxQi6QD3G7L9MYQcx","description":"Writing _bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-1-worktree-manager.md","usage":{"total_tokens":64730,"tool_uses":29,"duration_ms":132566},"last_tool_name":"Write","uuid":"d5923168-566e-48ad-a131-22462f1717ce","session_id":"187035da-d60e-40cf-8aef-09e6134be246"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RcmdQSGQGfiVLFxXrFXCbY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AK34mrVTb3DvxiqUxHaTWR","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/ivintik/dev/personal/codeharness/_bmad-output/implementation-artifacts/17-1-worktree-manager.md","content":"# Story 17.1: Worktree Manager\n\nStatus: ready-for-dev\n\n## Story\n\nAs a developer,\nI want a worktree manager that handles git worktree create/merge/cleanup,\nso that parallel epics run in isolated working directories.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n1. **Given** `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` exists, **when** `createWorktree(epicId, slug)` is called, **then** it creates a git branch named `codeharness/epic-{epicId}-{slug}` from the current HEAD of the main branch. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n2. **Given** `createWorktree(epicId, slug)` is called, **when** the branch is created, **then** it creates a git worktree at `/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{epicId}` pointing to the new branch and returns the absolute worktree path. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n3. **Given** `createWorktree(epicId, slug)` is called, **when** the operation completes, **then** the total wall-clock time is under 10 seconds (NFR1). <!-- verification: runtime-provable -->\n\n4. **Given** `cleanupWorktree(epicId)` is called, **when** a worktree exists for that epicId, **then** the worktree is removed via `git worktree remove` and the branch `codeharness/epic-{epicId}-*` is deleted via `git branch -D`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n5. **Given** `cleanupWorktree(epicId)` is called, **when** no worktree exists for that epicId, **then** the function completes without error (idempotent). <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n6. **Given** `listWorktrees()` is called, **when** one or more codeharness worktrees exist, **then** it returns an array of `WorktreeInfo` objects containing `epicId`, `path`, `branch`, and `createdAt` for every worktree whose branch starts with `codeharness/epic-`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n7. **Given** `listWorktrees()` is called, **when** no codeharness worktrees exist, **then** it returns an empty array. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n8. **Given** orphaned worktrees from a previous crashed run exist (worktree directory present but no active codeharness process), **when** `detectOrphans()` is called, **then** it returns an array of orphaned `WorktreeInfo` entries whose worktree paths are present on disk but not tracked by any running codeharness process. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n9. **Given** `createWorktree` is called, **when** the branch `codeharness/epic-{epicId}-{slug}` already exists (stale from a crash), **then** the function cleans up the stale branch and worktree before re-creating, rather than throwing. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n10. **Given** `createWorktree` is called, **when** the git command fails (e.g., not a git repo, disk full), **then** a descriptive `WorktreeError` is thrown with the stderr from the git command, and any partially-created branch or worktree is cleaned up. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n11. **Given** all git operations in worktree-manager, **when** they execute, **then** stderr is captured and included in error messages, and branch names are prefixed with `codeharness/` to avoid collision with user branches (NFR12). <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n\n## Tasks / Subtasks\n\n- [ ] Task 1: Create `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` with types and interfaces (AC: #1, #2, #6, #8, #11)\n  - [ ] Define `WorktreeInfo` interface: `epicId`, `path`, `branch`, `createdAt`\n  - [ ] Define `WorktreeError` error class extending `Error` with `stderr` field\n  - [ ] Define `WorktreeManager` class with constructor accepting `mainBranch: string` (default `'main'`)\n  - [ ] Constants: `BRANCH_PREFIX = 'codeharness/epic-'`, `WORKTREE_BASE = '/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-'`\n\n- [ ] Task 2: Implement `createWorktree(epicId, slug)` (AC: #1, #2, #3, #9, #10)\n  - [ ] Run `git branch codeharness/epic-{epicId}-{slug} {mainBranch}` via `execSync`\n  - [ ] Run `git worktree add /tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{epicId} codeharness/epic-{epicId}-{slug}` via `execSync`\n  - [ ] On branch-already-exists: call cleanup first, then retry create (AC #9)\n  - [ ] On any failure: clean up partial state (remove worktree if created, delete branch if created)\n  - [ ] Wrap git stderr in `WorktreeError`\n  - [ ] Return absolute worktree path\n\n- [ ] Task 3: Implement `cleanupWorktree(epicId)` (AC: #4, #5)\n  - [ ] Find the branch matching `codeharness/epic-{epicId}-*` via `git branch --list`\n  - [ ] Run `git worktree remove /tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{epicId} --force`\n  - [ ] Run `git branch -D {branch}` to delete the branch\n  - [ ] Swallow errors if worktree or branch doesn't exist (idempotent, AC #5)\n\n- [ ] Task 4: Implement `listWorktrees()` (AC: #6, #7)\n  - [ ] Run `git worktree list --porcelain` and parse output\n  - [ ] Filter to entries whose branch starts with `codeharness/epic-`\n  - [ ] Extract epicId from branch name pattern `codeharness/epic-{epicId}-{slug}`\n  - [ ] Return `WorktreeInfo[]` sorted by epicId\n\n- [ ] Task 5: Implement `detectOrphans()` (AC: #8)\n  - [ ] Call `listWorktrees()` to get all codeharness worktrees\n  - [ ] Check each worktree path for a `.codeharness/lane-state.json` file\n  - [ ] If lane-state.json doesn't exist or has no active PID, mark as orphan\n  - [ ] Return orphaned `WorktreeInfo[]`\n\n- [ ] Task 6: Write unit tests (AC: #1-#11)\n  - [ ] Test: createWorktree creates branch and worktree, returns path\n  - [ ] Test: createWorktree cleans up stale branch before re-creating\n  - [ ] Test: createWorktree throws WorktreeError with stderr on git failure\n  - [ ] Test: createWorktree cleans up partial state on failure\n  - [ ] Test: cleanupWorktree removes worktree and branch\n  - [ ] Test: cleanupWorktree is idempotent (no error when nothing exists)\n  - [ ] Test: listWorktrees returns only codeharness-prefixed worktrees\n  - [ ] Test: listWorktrees returns empty array when none exist\n  - [ ] Test: detectOrphans identifies worktrees without active process\n  - [ ] Test: branch names use codeharness/ prefix (NFR12)\n  - [ ] Test: all error messages include stderr from git\n\n## Dev Notes\n\n### Architecture Constraints\n\n- **Architecture Decision 1** (architecture-parallel-execution.md): Each parallel epic gets its own git worktree on a dedicated branch. The worktree manager handles the full lifecycle: create -> execute -> merge -> validate -> cleanup. This story covers create, cleanup, list, and orphan detection. Merge is deferred to Story 18-1.\n- **Worktree Operations Pattern**: All git operations MUST use `child_process.execSync` for atomic git commands (create branch, add worktree). Use `child_process.exec` with timeout for potentially slow operations. Capture stderr for error reporting. Clean up on failure.\n- **Branch naming**: `codeharness/` prefix prevents collision with user branches (NFR12).\n- **Worktree location**: `/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-{N}` -- temporary, cleaned up after merge.\n\n### Key Files to Create\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` | Git worktree lifecycle module |\n| `src/lib/__tests__/worktree-manager.test.ts` | Unit tests |\n\n### Key Files to Read (Do Not Modify)\n\n| File | Why |\n|------|-----|\n| `src/lib/hierarchical-flow.ts` | `ExecutionConfig` interface -- has `isolation: 'worktree' \\| 'none'`. Worktree manager is used when `isolation === 'worktree'`. |\n| `src/lib/null-task-registry.ts` | Pattern reference for registry modules with interfaces + error class. Follow the same module structure. |\n| `src/lib/telemetry-writer.ts` | Pattern reference for `appendFileSync`/`mkdirSync` file operations, `node:fs` imports, test patterns. |\n| `src/lib/session-manager.ts` | Pattern reference for `child_process` usage in this codebase. |\n\n### Implementation Patterns\n\n**Git command execution:**\n```typescript\nimport { execSync } from 'node:child_process';\n\n// Atomic git commands — use execSync\nexecSync(`git branch ${branchName} ${mainBranch}`, {\n  cwd: projectDir,\n  stdio: ['pipe', 'pipe', 'pipe'],  // capture stderr\n});\n\n// Parse git worktree list --porcelain output:\n// worktree /path/to/worktree\n// HEAD abc123\n// branch refs/heads/codeharness/epic-17-worktree-manager\n// (blank line)\n```\n\n**Error handling:**\n```typescript\ntry {\n  execSync(cmd, { cwd, stdio: ['pipe', 'pipe', 'pipe'] });\n} catch (err: unknown) {\n  const stderr = (err as { stderr?: Buffer })?.stderr?.toString() ?? '';\n  throw new WorktreeError(`Failed to create worktree: ${stderr}`, stderr);\n}\n```\n\n**Testing strategy:** Mock `execSync` with `vi.mock('node:child_process')`. Verify correct git commands are called with correct arguments. Test error paths by making mock throw with stderr buffer.\n\n### Previous Story (16-6) Intelligence\n\n- Story 16-6 completed the story flow execution. All 4779 tests pass. This is the first story in Epic 17 -- a new module with no modifications to existing files.\n- Recent code patterns: TypeScript modules in `src/lib/`, tests colocated in `__tests__/`, ESM with `.js` import extensions, vitest test framework.\n- Module pattern: export interfaces, export functions or class, export error class. JSDoc comments on all exports.\n- The workflow engine already has `ExecutionConfig` parsed from YAML. The worktree manager will be consumed by the lane pool (Story 17-2) and the merge serialization (Story 18-1).\n\n### Boundary: What This Story Does NOT Include\n\n- **Merge operations** -- deferred to Story 18-1. This story has no `mergeWorktree()` method.\n- **Lane pool integration** -- deferred to Story 17-2. The worktree manager is a standalone module.\n- **Run command integration** -- deferred to Story 17-3.\n- **TUI components** -- deferred to Epic 20.\n\n### Edge Cases\n\n- **Stale branch from crash**: If `codeharness/epic-17-slug` already exists when `createWorktree` is called, the previous run crashed. Clean up the stale state before re-creating (AC #9). Do not throw.\n- **Worktree directory already exists on disk**: `/tmp/codeharness-wt-epic-17` might exist from a crash. `git worktree add` will fail. Handle by removing the directory first.\n- **Not a git repo**: `execSync` throws. Wrap in `WorktreeError` with descriptive message.\n- **Branch name with special characters**: The `slug` parameter comes from epic names. Sanitize to `[a-z0-9-]` before using in branch name.\n- **Concurrent createWorktree calls**: Two calls with different epicIds are safe (different branches, different paths). Two calls with the same epicId are a bug in the caller -- the second will hit the stale-cleanup path.\n\n### Project Structure Notes\n\n- Source: TypeScript in `src/`, compiled to `dist/`\n- Tests: vitest, colocated in `src/lib/__tests__/` directories\n- ESM modules -- use `.js` extensions in imports\n- Build: `npm run build`\n- Test: `npm test`\n\n### References\n\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-parallel-execution.md#Story 17.1]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Decision 1 — Worktree Lifecycle Model]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Worktree Operations Pattern]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Architectural Boundaries — Worktree Manager]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd.md#FR6, FR7, FR11]\n- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd.md#NFR1, NFR9, NFR12]\n\n<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n## Verification Requirements\n\n- [ ] Showboat proof document created (verification/17-1-worktree-manager-proof.md)\n- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence via docker exec\n- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100%)\n\n## Documentation Requirements\n\n- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated\n- [ ] Exec-plan created in docs/exec-plans/active/17-1-worktree-manager.md\n\n## Testing Requirements\n\n- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n\n## Dev Agent Record\n\n### Agent Model Used\n\n{{agent_model_name_version}}\n\n### Debug Log References\n\n### Completion Notes List\n\n### File List\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3855,"cache_read_input_tokens":60375,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3855,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01MhSojYxQi6QD3G7L9MYQcx","session_id":"187035da-d60e-40cf-8aef-09e6134be246","uuid":"ee931c92-d685-483c-913a-23bc4eec1ae0"}
